# Coach-level rules (soft reminders). Two sections:
#   SECTION 1 = PORTABLE CORE — process/diagnostic discipline, NO project facts.
#               Moves to any project unchanged. This is the transferable core.
#   SECTION 2 = PROJECT PRINCIPLES — a general principle + {{facts}} pulled from
#               project.<name>.json. To port: change the facts, not these rules.
# fields: name | when (regex; bilingual matchers — you may prompt in CN or EN) | inject | on?
#
# ===================== SECTION 1: PORTABLE CORE (no facts) =====================
{"name": "debug-method", "when": "为什么|机械音|不对劲?|坏了|没用|还有问题|还不行|debug|诊断|排查|garbage|乱码|杂音", "inject": "[hansard:don't-guess] This kind of bug is usually SILENT (loss keeps dropping, train/infer are consistently wrong, \"it runs, just bad\"). (1) Default to \"bad output = a silent bug\", not under-training. (2) Pin the symptom to ONE layer (data/encode · decode-render · generation/sampling · training). (3) Reproduce THROUGH the model. (4) Root-cause down to \"a specific line diffed vs the reference\" or \"a probe number\" — ablation is measurement, not a story; don't narrate."}
{"name": "diagnose-rigor", "when": "为什么|为何|找原因|定位|排查|root.?cause|挂了|崩了?|hang|卡死|illegal|OOM|NaN|对比.{0,4}实验|ablation|bisect", "inject": "[hansard:diagnostic-rigor] (1) Don't guess serially — design >=2 FALSIFIABLE probes and run them in parallel, eliminate by result (serial guessing once took 4h; a bisection took 20min). (2) When a symptom has several variables (storage type / length / dtype / parallelism), change ONE at a time and name the confounds. (3) Don't declare a boundary (\"anything X>Y crashes\") from 2-3 points — build a bisection table."}
{"name": "data-sanity-first", "when": "illegal.?mem|CUDA.?error|backward.*(崩|错|fail)|errno|FileNotFound|读坏|corrupt|NaN|Inf", "inject": "[hansard:check-data-before-algorithm] When it crashes near IO/NCCL/OOM/NaN, first sample 10 files and load them + check for NaN/magnitude/existence; only AFTER confirming the input is clean, reach for bf16/attention numerical hypotheses. The real cause is often a corrupt read, not sequence length / numerical instability."}
{"name": "repro-at-scale", "when": "修好了|fixed|搞定|解决了|跑通了|应该.{0,3}(好|行|没问题)|work了|没问题了", "inject": "[hansard:reproduce-at-scale] A 1-step / short-run success != fixed. If the original failure happened at N steps, run >=N steps / at the original scale before declaring victory."}
{"name": "code-not-plan", "when": "架构|怎么实现|工作原理|interleave|讲一下.{0,8}(逻辑|实现|架构|思路)|how.{0,6}(does|work)|design.{0,6}(思路|是)", "inject": "[hansard:current-code-not-the-plan] Explain an architecture by stating what the code does NOW (file:line + one real trace) BEFORE what's planned; if current and planned differ, flag the gap explicitly."}
{"name": "spot-check-output", "when": "跑完|完成了|finished|生成好了|处理完|job.{0,6}(done|完成)|done\\b", "inject": "[hansard:spot-check-the-artifact] When a data/processing job finishes, don't trust exit-code + line-count alone. Sample 5-10 output records and check schema/NaN/format/fields before moving to the next stage — bad data silently poisons downstream training."}
{"name": "shape-flow-on-talk", "when": "接.{0,4}数据|对接.{0,6}(数据|模型|网络)|新.{0,3}数据集|换.{0,3}(数据|模型|网络)|改.{0,3}(数据|模型|网络|forward|loss|collate)|实现.{0,8}(网络|模型)|数据\\s*流|逐层|每一?层.{0,6}(output|输出|对)|喂.{0,6}模型|dataloader|collate_fn|new\\s+dataset|wire.{0,12}data|hook\\s*up.{0,12}data|implement.{0,12}(network|model)|data\\s*flow|shape.{0,12}(flow|mismatch|align|对不上|对齐)|layer.?by.?layer", "inject": "[hansard:derive-the-shape-flow] You're wiring data into a model or changing the model — do the cheap sanity check NOW, while designing, before/while you write code: DERIVE the end-to-end shape-flow yourself. Walk ONE batch dataloader -> every layer -> the loss scalar. For EACH step record three things, not just the shape: (a) symbolic shape (B,T,V,n_cb,mask_rate — symbols, not concrete numbers); (b) the MEANING of each axis (batch/time/vocab/codebook/stream?); (c) the ALIGNMENT INVARIANT a silent bug would break. The dangerous bugs are shape-COMPATIBLE but semantically wrong: in-place vs shifted loss (does logits[t] align with labels[t] or t+1?); a weight/mask that broadcasts onto the WRONG axis instead of the same [B,T]; an attention mask whose shape works but whose causal/bidirectional semantics are wrong; multi-stream layout axes. Do this YOURSELF — only escalate to the user when the derivation does NOT close. Persist the table to research/shapeflow.<active-project>.md; if one already exists, DIFF against it and flag which steps changed."}
{"name": "prove-wiring-on-cpu", "when": "smoke.?test|self.?test|selftest|sanity.?check|冒烟|跑通|快速.{0,4}(验证|测试|demo)|quick.{0,6}(demo|sanity|test|check)|probe.{0,10}(forward|mask|loss|causal|wiring|attention)|behavioral.{0,6}(probe|diff)|verify.{0,14}wiring|prove.{0,14}wiring|验证.{0,8}(接线|管线|wiring|forward|loss|管道)|上\\s*gpu|launch.{0,14}(gpu|full.?scale|大规模)", "inject": "[hansard:prove-the-wiring-on-cpu] Shapes matching is NOT proof. Before promoting new/changed forward·mask·loss code to a GPU or full-scale run, PROVE the wiring on CPU first. (1) Turn each ALIGNMENT INVARIANT from the shape-flow into a runnable ASSERT — in-place vs shifted (logits[t] vs labels[t], not t+1), a mask/weight landing on the right axis, attention causal-vs-bidirectional SEMANTICS. (2) Add >=1 BEHAVIORAL probe that checks MEANING not shape — e.g. perturb a FUTURE position and assert an EARLIER output is bit-identical (diff==0) iff causality holds; render the attention mask / loss-contributing positions as a grid you can eyeball. (3) Run it with a TINY RANDOM model — seconds, no checkpoint, no GPU. (4) Promote ONLY when green; a red or absent smoke means the GPU run is measuring a bug, not the model. This is the runnable half of [hansard:derive-the-shape-flow]."}
{"name": "no-leakage-across-splits", "when": "\\u5212\\u5206|\\u5207\\u5206|train.?val|train.?test|train/val|train/test|\\bsplit\\b|hold.?out|\\bdedup|\\u53bb\\u91cd|\\u91cd\\u590d\\u6837\\u672c|near.?dup|\\bleak|\\u6cc4\\u6f0f|\\u6cc4\\u9732|contaminat|\\u6c61\\u67d3|cross.?(split|set)", "inject": "[hansard:no-leakage-across-splits] The #1 way to fool yourself: duplicates or a shared identity leaking across train/val/test -> inflated eval, real-world collapse. (1) DEDUP on the FULL identity key BEFORE splitting (not a partial id) — one source cut into many windows/crops/chunks must land ENTIRELY on one side, never scattered (the classic: split by session_id while each session is many windows). (2) Check NEAR-duplicates across splits, not just exact: MinHash/SimHash for text, perceptual-hash or embedding distance for image/audio (real datasets have hit 90%+ cross-split leakage). (3) Split by GROUP (speaker/document/patient/scene), not by row. A score that is high BECAUSE the model saw the test item in training is not generalization — prove the split is clean before trusting any number."}
{"name": "train-infer-preprocessing-parity", "when": "preprocess|\\u9884\\u5904\\u7406|\\bresize\\b|\\u5f52\\u4e00\\u5316|normaliz|mean.?std|channel.?(order|first|last)|\\bRGB\\b|\\bBGR\\b|resampl|\\u91cd\\u91c7\\u6837|tokeniz|\\u5206\\u8bcd|augment|serving.?skew|train.{0,6}(infer|serving|test).{0,6}(mismatch|skew|\\u4e0d\\u4e00\\u81f4|\\u5dee)|\\u63a8\\u7406.{0,4}(\\u9884\\u5904\\u7406|\\u4e00\\u81f4)", "inject": "[hansard:train-infer-preprocessing-parity] Training-serving skew: the preprocessing that produces model inputs MUST be byte-identical between train and inference — resize fn, normalization mean/std/scale, channel order (RGB vs BGR), resample rate, tokenizer + its normalizer/version, padding & truncation direction. One mismatch silently degrades and never crashes (a channel swap alone cost ~4% mAP; a changed tokenizer normalizer breaks vocab alignment). (1) Share ONE preprocessing code path across train/eval/serve — don't reimplement it twice. (2) Pin every preprocessing param into config AND pin library versions. (3) Probe: push one real sample through BOTH paths and assert the resulting tensors are identical."}
{"name": "eval-set-contamination", "when": "benchmark|contaminat|\\u6570\\u636e\\u6c61\\u67d3|\\u8bc4\\u6d4b\\u96c6|\\u6d4b\\u8bc4\\u96c6|held.?out|MMLU|GSM8K|HellaSwag|HumanEval|leaderboard|\\u8dd1\\u5206|gen.?ppl|generative.?perplex|test.?set.{0,12}(train|pretrain|\\u8bed\\u6599)|canary", "inject": "[hansard:eval-set-contamination] A benchmark only measures generalization if the model never saw it in training. Before trusting an eval/benchmark number: (1) Check the eval/test set is NOT present (exact OR near-duplicate) in the training/pretraining corpus — for web-scale LLM data this is the default, not the exception. (2) Prefer a held-out set drawn AFTER a known data cutoff, or a contamination-resistant / canary'd benchmark, over a public one likely already crawled. (3) If you cannot rule contamination out, LABEL the number 'possibly contaminated' rather than reporting it as clean generalization."}
{"name": "filler-is-not-neutral", "when": "\\bpad(ding)?\\b|\\u586b\\u5145|\\u5360\\u4f4d|np\\.zeros|torch\\.zeros|zeros?_like|\\u9759\\u97f3|silence|blank|black.?(frame|image)|mask.?token|ignore.?index|\\-100\\b|\\u7a7a\\u767d\\u5e27", "inject": "[hansard:filler-is-not-neutral] Any placeholder you insert — pad token, np.zeros, a silence clip, a black frame, a [MASK] — is a REAL input the model sees, not a harmless blank. Two failure modes: (a) it gets ENCODED to something out-of-distribution (a frozen codec maps pure zeros to a junk code; black frames are off-manifold), and (b) it leaks into the LOSS as a target the model learns to emit. (1) Check what your filler actually encodes/embeds to — don't assume 'zero == nothing'. (2) MASK filler positions out of the loss (ignore_index / a loss mask on the SAME [B,T] grid), and report the % of filler in your targets. (3) If a region must be filled, prefer an in-distribution fill (e.g. low-level noise over digital silence) over a hard zero."}
#
# ================ SECTION 2: PROJECT PRINCIPLES (general + {{facts}}) ===========
{"name": "train-data", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|run_?train|train\\.(py|sh)|训练|开训|重新?\\s*train|train\\s*吧|去\\s*train|跑.{0,4}(训|模型|实验|run)|launch.{0,10}train", "inject": "[hansard:verify-target-distribution] Before burning GPU, dump one real sample on CPU and look at the target: (1) no-op/padding is NOT a harmless zero — a frozen tokenizer encodes it to OOD codes that become training targets (check %OOD). (2) Weight the loss for the distribution you WANT at inference; when one class dominates, compute each class's effective gradient share. (3) Confirm the training field is the clean source. This project's traps: {{target_dist_traps}}."}
{"name": "train-infra", "when": "sbatch|torchrun|run_?train|train\\.(py|sh)|训练|开训|重新?\\s*train|train\\s*吧|去\\s*train|跑.{0,4}(训|模型|实验|run)|launch.{0,10}train|多节点|multi.?node|deepspeed|ds_config", "inject": "[hansard:training-infra] (1) Training reads MUST be on fast, reliable storage ({{good_storage}}); a networked/lazy FS corrupts under concurrent load -> crash; for multi-node, pre-copy to /dev/shm and verify the file count. (2) Config from multiple sources silently overrides — print the EFFECTIVE value ({{config_override_example}}). (3) Hyperparameters don't transfer across regimes ({{regime_example}}). (4) Under ZeRO, a custom sidecar save needs .detach().clone().contiguous() first."}
{"name": "shm-stale-cache", "when": "/dev/shm|--nnodes\\s*=?\\s*[2-9]|ntasks-per-node|多节点.*(暂存|stage)|追加.*(数据|codes)", "inject": "[hansard:stale-staged-cache] After appending data to a /dev/shm cache that nodes already staged, stale nodes use the old snapshot -> FileNotFoundError -> one rank dies -> multi-GPU NCCL hangs. Staging must COMPARE source vs staged file counts; on mismatch, FORCE_RESTAGE."}
{"name": "fresh-ckpt", "when": "续训|resume|warm.?start|断点续|接着.{0,6}(训|练|ckpt|checkpoint)|从.{0,8}(ckpt|checkpoint).{0,6}(训|练|续|接)|继续训练|continue.{0,6}train", "inject": "[hansard:don't-continue-a-poisoned-ckpt] A ckpt trained on a wrong target/loss is POISONED ({{poison_example}}). Always retrain fresh from a clean {{reference_impl}} and fix the cause via data/loss/hparams — don't continue-train from a bad ckpt."}
{"name": "demo-discipline", "when": "demo|效果|发我|发你|听.{0,2}听|render|生成.{0,4}音频|\\.wav|感觉.{0,4}(烂|差|怪|好|更)|好像.{0,4}(烂|差|更|不对)|sounds|变差", "inject": "[hansard:demo/eval-discipline] (1) A demo MUST go end-to-end through the model (generate); never pass off a GT codec round-trip / any proxy as a demo — first point at the line that called model.generate. (2) Label every demo: ckpt-id + which fixes are in it + key preprocessing params ({{demo_param}}). (3) Don't chase a subjective \"sounds worse\" by editing configs — get/produce a concrete sample+ckpt comparison first. (4) Objective metrics only narrow the range; the final call is the ear."}
{"name": "code-align", "when": "\\bloss\\b|权重|weight|speech_mask|\\bmask\\b|ar.?shift|采样|sampler|温度|temperature|kv.?cache|is_causal", "inject": "[hansard:custom-code-drifts-from-reference] Editing training code = you drifted from a verified reference; assume you broke it: (1) diff line-by-line vs {{reference_impl}}, log a reason for each divergence. (2) AR off-by-one: loss MUST be logits[:,:-1] vs labels[:,1:] — don't echo the input. (3) Every flag that affects the forward pass must match across train/infer and be written into config. This project's traps: {{code_align_example}}."}
{"name": "codec", "when": "encode|编码|mel|tokenizer|codec|codebook|码本|silence|静音|量化|\\bvq\\b|power=|re-?encode|重新.{0,4}编码", "inject": "[hansard:frozen-component-quirks] A frozen tokenizer/codec is a black box: (1) preprocessing params must match its training config bit-for-bit — don't trust library defaults. (2) no-op regions are OOD — check what they actually encode to. (3) {{codec_quirks}} (4) a weak modality learns a shortcut and ignores the strong condition — quantify with ablation, then add anti-shortcut pressure."}
# --- eval VALIDITY (how to read eval results; general to any model eval) ---
{"name": "eval-metric-by-region", "when": "ablation|accuracy|top-?1|准确率|\\bmetric\\b|指标|评测|\\beval\\b", "inject": "[hansard:beware-trivial-majority] An aggregate metric can be dominated by a trivially-predictable MAJORITY class (silence/empty/padding). Split it by region: speech vs silence, answer vs pre-answer. We got burned: {{eval_region_example}}."}
{"name": "eval-free-not-tf", "when": "teacher.?forc|tf.?acc|准确率|free.?run|自由生成|teacher 强制|强制解码", "inject": "[hansard:free-running-is-the-test] Teacher-forced per-cb accuracy OVERSTATES (the past is always GT; continuing the next frame is easy). The real test is free-running autoregressive generation (one sampling error and it collapses). High TF + garbage free-running = the classic shortcut signature."}
{"name": "eval-no-crutch", "when": "onset.?floor|force.?text|forced.?text|blank.*history|crutch|强制.*(起说|文本)|inject.?text|拐杖", "inject": "[hansard:no-eval-crutch] If a good score depends on help that deployment won't have ({{eval_crutch_example}}), it's not a real score. Eval conditions must EQUAL deployment conditions; label crutched numbers \"holds only under this condition\"."}
{"name": "eval-as-deployment", "when": "offline.*render|streamA_offline|full.?window|streaming|流式|encode_refresh|encode_chunked|离线.*渲染", "inject": "[hansard:eval-under-deployment-conditions] Offline render / full-window encode measures a DIFFERENT scenario than streaming deployment ({{eval_deploy_example}}). Eval under deployment-equivalent conditions, or run both tracks and label the gap."}
{"name": "concept-gap-quiz", "level": "escalate", "sticky": true, "when": "(?=[\\s\\S]*(?:是啥|啥意思|什么意思|是什么|什么区别|啥区别|有什么.{0,4}(?:不同|区别)|怎么.{0,4}(?:理解|区分)|没.{0,4}(?:看懂|懂|明白)|看不懂|不明白|不太懂|这是.{0,4}干(?:啥|嘛|什么)|what is|what'?s an?|what does .{1,25} mean|what'?s the difference|how do(?:es)? .{1,30} work|don'?t (?:get|understand|follow)|confused about|never (?:heard|seen)))(?=[\\s\\S]*(?:codec|DAC|RVQ|VQ|codebook|mel|spectrogram|vocoder|tokeniz|token|teacher.?forc|autoregress|MTP|MoE|Megatron|transformer|attention|mask|logit|softmax|embedding|quantiz|sample.?rate|ASR|CER|WER|duplex|streaming|checkpoint|ckpt|LoRA|fine.?tun|SFT|RLHF|epoch|gradient|loss|perplex|OOD|semantic|acoustic|frame.?rate|hop.?length|vocab|latent|diffusion|flow.?match|onset|encoder|decoder|encode|decode|quantizer|\\bs1\\b|\\bs2\\b|\\bs3\\b|\\bAR\\b))", "inject": "[hansard:concept-gap] A concept just came up that's easy to half-understand — research+engineering is full of them (codec/DAC/s2/RVQ/teacher-forcing…), and a fuzzy one keeps biting silently. Don't just re-explain and move on: (1) QUIZ them FIRST — one sharp question to surface what they actually hold — then (2) define it in PLAIN language (no jargon, why it matters HERE) and correct whatever the answer missed. (3) Record it in research/glossary.<active-project>.jsonl as {term, plain, why} so the gap is tracked, not re-hit."}
